      "colorPalette": "# Red for Joy, Gold for Wealth\n\nThe palette is built on two ceremonial anchors of a traditional Chinese wedding.\n\n## Lacquer Red — 红 (Joy)\n- **Header / chrome:** `#6E1A16` — deep lacquer red, the ceremonial ground.\n- **Rail & card surface:** `#8C2420` — brighter lacquer for hongbao-style guest cards.\n- **Ink on light:** `#4A1512` — dark red-brown for headings and body over porcelain.\n\n## Gilt Gold — 金 (Wealth)\n- **Gilt:** `#C4A053` — avatars, medallion, borders, primary buttons.\n- **Soft gold:** `#E6CF9A` — highlights and gradient top.\n- **Gold gradient:** `linear-gradient(135deg, #EBD9A0, #C4A053 55%, #A07A3C)`.\n\n## Porcelain Ground — 瓷 (Calm)\n- **Paper:** `#FBF4E6` — warm rice-paper canvas.\n- **Surface:** `#FFFDF8` — porcelain-white panels that let red and gold sing.\n\nGold is the metal, red is the mood. Reserve saturated red for the chrome and guest cards; keep the working surfaces porcelain so dense seating information stays legible.",
      "contentVoice": null,
      "inspirations": [
        "囍 double-happiness paper-cuts",
        "Hongbao (red envelopes) — lacquer red with gold foil",
        "Ming lacquerware and gilt hairlines",
        "Imperial banquet scrolls — Noto Serif SC brush weight",
        "Red-and-gold wedding poster typography"
      ],
      "designMindset": "# Ceremony Without Clutter\n\nThe banquet is festive, but a seating tool must stay readable. Concentrate the saturated lacquer red in the chrome (header, rails) and the hongbao guest cards; keep every working surface on warm porcelain so the room chart and roster remain scannable. Gold is a hairline and a medallion, not a fill — it accents structure rather than shouting. Every red is warm, every gold is aged rather than brassy: the effect should feel like an heirloom invitation, not a decoration store.",
